title: For Sale/Trade:  Rare Excellent 581 Mini-14 Stainless/Laminate
postcontent:
For sale or trade is an almost new 581 series Mini 14 Ranch rifle which was a Davidson's Exclusive Limited Edition model no5858. Ruger doesn't make these any more! There is absolutely nothing wrong with the weapon, perfect operating condition. I really love this gun, no cheap plastics, just good, solid stainless steel and laminate. Perfect for hunting in less than ideal weather without any worries. I am willing to FTF or ship at buyer's expense.

It has less than 100 rounds through it so the magazines and the action aren't even fully broken in. Function has been 100% out of box with several types of 5.56 and .223 ammo. I never benched it out to 100 yards, but it is definitely more accurate than I am with iron sights.

The laminated stock is a very nice black/grey with a slight greenish tint to it. I believe it was made under contract by Revolution but is a slightly different pattern from their Explorer stocks. I've made a few modifications to the stock for better ergonomics as it originally left much to be desired. The stock has a very few and very small handling marks, still in very good condition. It also has an excellent non-slip recoil pad.

Also included are two practically brand new Ruger factory magazines: one 20 rounder and one 30 rounder. Stainless steel scope rings, an upgraded handguard made by Choate for better ventilation and weight reduction, 120 rounds of mixed Tula and American Eagle, and three 5.56 dummy rounds by Magpul as an extra. 

The stock alone is worth around $200, the mags are between $35-$40 each, and the Choate handguard was $20 well spent, and ammo is worth around $50. All together it's worth a good $950.

Newport is a “private label” brand. Private label brands are produced by reputable companies but sold through outlets such as hardware and general stores under different names. “Newport” is stamped into the receiver left side along with the letter “N” inside a star.  

I got this shotgun in the 1980’s from a neighbor who said it was bought new by her grandfather (no dates or details). I thought it would make a nice display piece. title: For Sale/Trade:  Charter Arms AR7 Survival Rifle and Scope
location: North or Northwest Side, Indianapolis, Indiana
postcontent:
Since 1959, the AR-7 has been used by U.S. Air Force pilots that need a light-weight, small-caliber survival rifle. This AR-7, made circa 1987, was manufactured by Charter Arms.  While Charter no longer makes this model, it is the same basic model as the current AR-7 made by Henry.  The barrel, magazine and receiver disassemble in seconds without tools and fit inside the waterproof butt stock.  The rifle will float if dropped in water in either configuration.  The magazine stows in the butt stock loaded or unloaded.  It has a thumb safety and adjustable sights.

This is a great little "back pack" rifle for taking camping, etc.  It also makes a great first rifle.

This particular rifle has fired only about 300 to 500 rounds (very little use over the years - that is why I am selling it.)  Back when it was used, there were no failures to load or fire that I can recall.  As with all AR-7’s, it should be very reliable if you don’t use under-powered ammo.  The 8-round magazine (which contains the feed ramp) is in great shape and should feed well.

This rifle has just been completely disassembled, inspected, cleaned and lubricated and is in great shape.  It has light cosmetic wear marks - mostly on the shiny plastic stock.

While this rifle wasn’t originally designed to use a scope, I had fitted it with one and I am including it and the mounts in the price. The price is firm at $150 for a face-to-face transaction.

If I need to ship this, I will only ship to a FFL and the cost will be $150 + $40 to cover the additional fee that my local FFL charges me to process and ship.

postcontent:
For sale  is a 1939 Lee-Enfield No. 1 Mk. III SMLE, manufactured by BSA & Co. in 1939.  Manufactured for commercial sale, this is the last year BSA ever made SMLE's for the civilian market, switching to wartime production in the fall of '39.  

Magazine cutoff is correct and present. 

Refurbished at the Lithgow, Australia arsenal sometime in the '50's, this rifle is in excellent mechanical condition.  Receiver and nosecap match, the barrel was replaced during the refurb.  Spotless rifling, immaculate bore, no muzzle erosion.  The buttstock is marked "WA" (Western Australia) and "AID" (Australian Interior Defence) with an acceptance mark on the other side;  meaning this gun was issued to police or militia units postwar.  Comes with a period-correct sling and 25 rounds of .303 surplus mounted on stripper clips.

title: For Sale:  1916 Lee-Enfield SMLE No. 1 Mk. III Ishapore wire-wrap
postcontent:
Up for sale is a 1916 Lee-Enfield No. 1 Mk. III, manufactured at Enfield-on-Lock;  later converted at the Indian Rifle Factory Ishapore in 1928 to a wire-wrapped grenade launching model, this rifle is 100% original.  The RFI conversion stamp is on the left-hand side of the receiver wrist. 

* Receiver, nosecap, bolt, and rear sight all bear the same serial;  the wire-wrap prevents looking at the forestock and barrel, but it is very likely those are matching as well. Wire wrap present and unbroken. 

* 75% rifling still present, a few areas of frosting and very light pitting, but still very strong.  The "bullet test" for muzzle erosion still shows just over 1/16" of copper. 

* Receiver/barrel stamped EY

* Buttstock is still tight, upper handguards in good shape, no cracking. 

* Cutoff still present!  

* Comes with 25 rounds of surplus .303 and a period-correct sling.  

Asking $375, willing to drive a reasonable distance from my home in Northern Akron to make the right deal.  Would prefer a face to face sale, will ship to a valid FFL or Type 3 C&R, buyer pays shipping. Please message with any questions, or text REDACTED for more pictures and info.  Thanks for looking!
